blockquote.p: “Generate a marketing site for a solar startup”

div.p: and your tool scaffolds ready-to-deploy HTML, CSS, and JS templates using an LLM.
Here’s the tech stack I recommend based on your problem statement:

li.p: For building the CLI tool and handling file generation.
Provides filesystem APIs to write generated HTML/CSS/JS files.
Takes the user prompt.
Generates HTML/CSS/JS boilerplate, page layout, and placeholder content.
For development, debugging, and testing generated sites.
Commander.js → Build the CLI commands (npx prompt-site "Generate X").
Inquirer.js → Interactive prompts (ask user for site type, color theme, etc.).
Axios / fetch → Make API calls to Gemini API.
Prettier → Format generated code for clean output.
fs (Node built-in) → Write scaffolds into /output folder.
Live Server / Vite (optional) → Preview the generated site locally.
Ready to deploy on Netlify / Vercel / GitHub Pages.

/** * High-level orchestrator: * - Produces index.html (with basic nav for pages) * - Optionally produces style.css * - Optionally produces script.js */
{ prompt, theme, pages, includeCSS, includeJS } = config;

htmlInstruction = ` You are generating the main HTML for a static website.
Context: - Brief:

Requirements: - Produce a complete, valid HTML5 document. - Create a responsive navbar with links for the listed pages (anchors/hrefs). - Add hero section with a strong headline & subtext tailored to the brief. - Add at least two supporting sections (features, testimonials, or CTA). - Use semantic tags (header, main, section, footer). - Do not inline large CSS or JS; link to style.css and script.js if they exist. - Keep placeholder copy realistic and concise. - Never include <script type="module"> or frameworks—just vanilla. Return ONLY the HTML, nothing else. `;

cssInstruction = ` You are generating the CSS for a static site.
Design keywords:

Requirements: - Define CSS variables for a primary color, accent, text, background. - Make it clean, modern, and accessible (contrast). - Include responsive rules (mobile-first). - Style a header/navbar, hero, sections, buttons, cards, footer. Return ONLY the CSS, nothing else. `;

jsInstruction = ` You are generating minimal vanilla JS enhancements for a static site.
Requirements: - Add a mobile nav toggle for small screens. - Add smooth scrolling for local anchor links. - Keep code small, framework-free, and robust. Return ONLY the JS, nothing else. `;

span.span: "Landing page for a solar startup that sells affordable rooftop panels"

hr.p: This will create a folder solar-landing/ with index.html, style.css, script.js, favicon.svg, robots.txt, and a README.md.

li.p:
Split prompts per file (HTML/CSS/JS):
You get more predictable, clean outputs vs. asking the model to return multiple blobs together.

System prompt kept small:
Small, focused constraints tend to produce more consistent code than giant “everything” prompts.

Prettier on write:
Keeps diffs clean if you regenerate.

Commander + Inquirer:
Smooth UX—flags for automation, interactive for casual use.

No frameworks:
Your output must work on any static host (GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel).
Add --framework tailwind to optionally generate Tailwind scaffolds.
Add --assets to ask Gemini for royalty-free image ideas & alt text.
Add multi-page generation (create /about.html, /contact.html) and cross-link them.
Add a --template switch to blend LLM output with a base HTML skeleton from /templates.

hr.p: If you want, I can extend this to multi-page generation right away and add a Vite preview command.

When you see -p in Linux commands, it usually means “make parent directories if needed”. In PowerShell, you don’t need -p because mkdir (alias for New-Item -ItemType Directory) already creates the folders without error if the path doesn’t exist.
